::: {layout="[[1,1], [1]]"} ![](images/logos/takuvik.svg) ![](images/logos/sn.png) ![](images/logos/ulaval.svg) ::: ::: ::: {.column width='5%'} ::: ::: {.column width='55%'} [Research assistant at Takuvik (Laval University)]{style="font-weight:bold;font-size:1.5em"} *Remote sensing, modelling, data science, data visualization*
{{< fa brands github >}} [My GitHub](https://github.com/PMassicotte){style="font-weight:bold;"} {{< fa brands twitter >}} [Follow me on Twitter](https://twitter.com/philmassicotte){style="font-weight:bold;"} {{< fa brands mastodon >}} [Follow me on Mastodon](https://fosstodon.org/@philmassicotte){style="font-weight:bold;"} {{< fa link >}} [www.pmassicotte.com](https://www.pmassicotte.com){style="font-weight:bold;"} ::: :::: ## Training workshop on data management and archiving {style="text-align:center;"}

:::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='60%'}
March 15th 2023 **Inscriptions:** [https://bit.ly/3ZcH96P](https://bit.ly/3ZcH96P)
::: ::: {.column width='40%'} [Outline]{style="font-size:1.5em;font-weight:bold"} ::: {.small} - Intellectual Property of Data - Data management plan - Data acquisition - Data cataloguing and dissemination - Standards, processing, standardization and importance of metadata ::: ::: :::: ## Context :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='70%'} ::: ::: {.column width='30%'} > [**It is often said that 80% of data analysis is spent on cleaning and preparing data.** And it's not just a first step, but it must be repeated many over the course of analysis as new problems come to light or new data is collected.]{style="font-size:0.9em;"} ::: :::: ## Context :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='70%'} ::: ::: {.column width='30%'} > [Data preprocessing is one of the main steps in the data science project life cycle which involves **converting raw data into a refined form amenable to data analysis**. [Source: towards data science](https://towardsdatascience.com/three-critical-elements-of-data-preprocessing-part-2-2078110ae8e7)]{style="font-size:0.9em;"} ::: :::: ## Objectives ::: {.incremental} - [**Part 1 (~ 2 hours)**]{style="font-size:1.25em"} - Understand the basics of data manipulation techniques using R. - Learn how to clean and transform raw data into a format suitable for analysis using `dplyr` and `tidyr`. - Develop the ability to manipulate and analyze datasets: **grouping**, **filtering** and **summarizing**. - Acquire knowledge on how to **join, merge and aggregate data** from multiple sources to produce meaningful insights. - [**Part 2 (~ 1 hour)**]{style="font-size:1.25em"} 1. Working on your own data 2. Data challenge: *SQL Murder Mystery* ::: ## Who are you? - Diverse faculties and academic backgrounds. - Efforts to offer examples that are pertinent to everyone in the classroom. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-2_36c77eb826847d18882155d9d63e9b58'} ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-2-1.png){width=3000} ::: ::: ## Prerequisites - This workshop **is not** an introduction to R programming. - I am assuming that you already have basic knowledge of R. - You should know how to: - Install R packages - Use R Studio or another of your choice - Create R scripts - Import data - Work with data frame - Perform basic calculations ## Getting ready to code! If you do not have R/R Studio installed on your laptop, I have created a pre-configured cloud instance of R with all the packages needed for this workshop. If you choose this option, you need to have a free [Posit](https://posit.cloud) account. - **Step 1:** Open the course project - Go to this URL: [https://posit.cloud/spaces/338666/](https://posit.cloud/spaces/338666/). - You will have to create or login into your Posit account first.

- **Step 2:** Make a copy of the project ::: footer ::: # Data frames {background-color="#2C404A"} ## Data frames ::: {.incremental} - **Data frames** are important objects in R which are created when reading (most) tabular text files. - The most useful data structure for data scientists. - They allow for efficient data manipulation: - Filtering - Summarizing - Aggregating - Joining - And much more! ::: ## Data frames - A data frame can be seen as an Excel tabular sheet: **Lines are observations** and **columns are variables**. ::: {.callout-note} A data frame can be seen as a matrix with the difference that **columns (variables) can be of different types** (numerics, dates, characters, etc.). ::: ## Data frames The `mtcars` data frame is included in base R. :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='40%'} > The data was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (1973–74 models). ::: ::: {.column width='60%' .small} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-3_f2d7e45df4c5f39f02666aab10ef3e80'} ```{.r .cell-code} mtcars ``` ::: {.cell-output 2.780 18.60 1 1 4 2 ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: # Importing data in R {background-color="#2C404A"} ## Reading files - Why bother about **data frame**? Most of the time, this is the data structure that will be created when importing data in R. - There are many functions to import data in R. | **File format** | **Function** | **Package** | |------------------------------------|----------------|-------------| | Comma separated values (.csv) | `read_csv()` | readr | | Other text files (.txt, .dat, ...) | `read_delim()` | readr | | Excel (.xls, .xlsx) | `read_excel()` | readxl | | Stata | `read_stata()` | haven | | SPSS | `read_spss()` | haven | | SAS | `read_sas()` | haven | | Matlab file (.mat) | `readMat()` | R.matlab | ## Reading Excel files :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='80%'} To read Excel files, we can use `read_excel()` from the `readxl` package. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-4_9250a135b2281f79614eaf6509fcaee9'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-2|4-5|7-8"} # Load the readxl package library(readxl) # Read the first sheet in a file mydata <- read_excel("/path/to/myfile.xls") # Read the third sheet in a file mydata <- read_excel("/path/to/myfile.xlsx", sheet = 3) ``` ::: ::: ::: {.column width='20%'} ![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tidyverse/readxl/main/img/readxl.png){width=400} ::: :::: ## Reading CSV files :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='80%'} To read CSV files, we can use `read_csv()` from the `readr` package. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-5_cede236b71416381227c6c24f34a4dd3'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-2|4-5|7-8"} # Load the readr package library(readr) # If the column delimiter is "," mydata <- read_csv("/path/to/myfile.csv") # If the column delimiter is ";" mydata <- read_csv2("/path/to/myfile.csv") ``` ::: ::: ::: {.column width='20%'} ![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rstudio/hex-stickers/main/PNG/readr.png){width=400} ::: :::: :::: {.fragment} ::: {.callout-important} Note that the base R function to read a CSV file is `read.csv()`. Do not confuse with the `read_csv()` function from `readr`. ::: :::: ## Reading files online It is also possible to read files hosted online by providing an URL. For example, let's read daily weather updates from the Curiosity Rover on Mars. ::: {.small} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-6_af608a145c32b67a3dda952e27cafd2b'} ```{.r .cell-code} mars <- read_csv("https://query.data.world/s/nig6iktbywlhnws22gfz6tvstwtmuu") mars ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1,894 × 10 id terrestrial…¹ sol ls month min_t…² max_t…³ press…⁴ wind_…⁵ atmo_…⁶ 1 1895 2018-02-27 1977 135 Mont… -77 -10 727 NaN Sunny 2 1893 2018-02-26 1976 135 Mont… -77 -10 728 NaN Sunny 3 1894 2018-02-25 1975 134 Mont… -76 -16 729 NaN Sunny 4 1892 2018-02-24 1974 134 Mont… -77 -13 729 NaN Sunny 5 1889 2018-02-23 1973 133 Mont… -78 -18 730 NaN Sunny 6 1891 2018-02-22 1972 133 Mont… -78 -14 730 NaN Sunny 7 1890 2018-02-21 1971 132 Mont… -78 -13 731 NaN Sunny 8 1888 2018-02-20 1970 132 Mont… -77 -16 731 NaN Sunny 9 1887 2018-02-19 1969 131 Mont… -76 -16 732 NaN Sunny 10 1886 2018-02-18 1968 131 Mont… -76 -19 732 NaN Sunny # … with 1,884 more rows, and abbreviated variable names ¹​terrestrial_date, # ²​min_temp, ³​max_temp, ⁴​pressure, ⁵​wind_speed, ⁶​atmo_opacity ``` ::: ::: ::: ## Reading files online ::: {.cell layout-align="center" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-7_45188590dfce5ef8a14636f1632acee7'} ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){fig-align='center' width=2100} ::: ::: ## Exporting data Similarly, exporting a data frame into a file can be done using: `write_*()`. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-8_5cb0b8f59b3b787b9760f519e8ccee7a'} ```{.r .cell-code} write_csv(df, "/path/to/myfile.csv") write_csv2(df, "/path/to/myfile.csv") write_tsv(df, "/path/to/myfile.tsv") write_delim(df, "/path/to/myfile.tab") ``` ::: For example, you could export the `mtcars` data frame in tab-delimited and comma-delimited files on your desktop: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-9_0660de567f6a976139bfb4dc85adcabc'} ```{.r .cell-code} write_delim(mtcars, "~/Desktop/mtcars.tab") write_csv(mtcars, "~/Desktop/mtcars.csv") ``` ::: ## What is a `tibble`? :::: {.columns}
::: {.column width='60%'} [In base R, the main object holding **sheet-like data** is called a `data.frame`. In the `tidyverse` ecosystem, they are called `tibble`, which can be seen as **a pimped version** of a `data.frame`.]{style="line-height:2.5"} ::: ::: {.column width='40%'}
::: :::: ## What is a `tibble`? :::: {.columns .small} ::: {.column width="50%"} [Reading using base R creates a `data.frame`]{style="font-size:1.3em;"} ::: {.cell # Manipulating data in R {background-color="#2C404A"} ## Data manipulation There are two main characteristics of good data manipulation: . . . 1. **speed**: results are returned in a reasonable time . . . 2. **elegance**: easy to use and to understand what the code is doing . . . > The **tidyverse** is an opinionated collection of R packages designed for data science. All packages share an underlying design philosophy, grammar, and data structures. ## The tidyverse The tidyverse provides a set of packages which provides flexible tools for data manipulation.
## The tidyverse The package is not included in the base installation of R. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-12_e02f71f0e1ee218f2b4b2128c38edbba'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install the tidyverse packages install.packages("tidyverse") ``` ::: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-13_5057a0658ace49fc6c400ed010789eb7'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Load all the packages included in tidyverse library(tidyverse) ``` ::: You can refer to the printed **cheat sheet** for an overview of the package's functions. # Data manipulation with {dplyr} {background-color="#2C404A"} ## dplyr > dplyr is a grammar of data manipulation, providing a consistent set of verbs that help you solve the most common data manipulation challenges All `dplyr` functions use the same scheme: **the first argument to provide is a data frame**. | **Function** | **Definition** | |------------------------|-----------------------------------------------| | `filter(df, ...)` | Select a subset of the rows of a data frame. | | `arrange(df, ...)` | Reorder rows of a data frame. | | `select(df, ...)` | Select columns of a data frame. | | `mutate(df, ...)` | Add or modify columns in a data frame. | | `summarise(df, ...)` | Summarize a data frame into a single row. This function is very helpful in combination with the `group_by()` function. | | `group_by(df, ...)` | Group a data frame based on the specified columns. | : Useful functions {tbl-colwidths="[25,75]"} ## The `nycflights13` datasets ::: {.incremental} - To learn how to use these functions, we will use datasets from package `nycflights13`. - This package contains information about all flights that departed from New York airports (i.e., **EWR**, **JFK** and **LGA**) in 2013. - Not included in base R, we first need to install it. ::: . . . ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-14_9c89c0d8ad89955719a8b72669c826fe'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install the dataset package install.packages("nycflights13") ``` ::: ## Relationships - The `flights` table connects to planes via a single variable, `tailnum`. - The `flights` table connects to `airports` in two ways: via the `origin` and `dest` variables. ## nycflights13 For the following examples we are going to use **fights**, **planes**, **airports**, **airlines** tables. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-15_5a9f8b8d5359feec6ad8e4891ac5de22'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Libraries for data manipulation and visualization library(tidyverse) # Load the data package library(nycflights13) # Loads all the five data frame included in nycflights13 data(flights) data(planes) data(airports) data(airlines) data(weather) ``` ::: ## The `mutate()` function is used to add or modify existing column(s) inside a data frame. - The function takes a data frame, and one or more expressions that add/modify columns. ## The `mutate()` function Example 1: add a new column named `distance_km` which converts the `distance` column, which is the flight distance in miles, into km. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-35_463d422bf7c1c6b8a1b3284f738382c2'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-5|2|3|4|1-5"} mutate( flights, distance_km = distance / 0.62137, .keep = "used" ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 336,776 × 2 distance distance_km 1 1400 2253.1 2 1416 2278.8 3 1089 1752.6 4 1576 2536.3 5 762 1226.3 6 719 1157.1 7 1065 1714.0 8 229 368.54 9 944 1519.2 10 733 1179.7 # … with 336,766 more rows ``` ::: ::: ## The `mutate()` function It is also possible to add many new variables in a single operation. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-36_5ef405a735f0cf28345c7d7658d00a87'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="3-4|1-6"} mutate( flights, distance_km = distance / 0.62137, distance_knot = distance / 1.15078, .keep = "used" ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 336,776 × 3 distance distance_km distance_knot 1 1400 2253.1 1216.6 2 1416 2278.8 1230.5 3 1089 1752.6 946.31 4 1576 2536.3 1369.5 5 762 1226.3 662.16 6 719 1157.1 624.79 7 1065 1714.0 925.46 8 229 368.54 199.00 9 944 1519.2 820.31 10 733 1179.7 636.96 # … with 336,766 more rows ``` ::: ::: ## The `mutate()` function The `mutate()` function is very powerful as it allows to use of some **helper functions** to **mutate multiple columns at once**. One option, is to use the `across(cols, function_to_apply)` function. - The following code says: [apply the `mean()` function to all the columns between `temp` and `pressure`]{.text-outline} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-40_bcbe018ac9dcdf6afbe1b7b4f373a1bf'} ```{.r .cell-code} mutate(weather, across(year:pressure, round), .keep = "used") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 26,115 × 12 year month day hour temp dewp humid wind_dir wind_speed wind_g…¹ precip 1 2013 1 1 1 39 26 59 270 10 NA 0 2 2013 1 1 2 39 27 62 250 8 NA 0 3 2013 1 1 3 39 28 64 240 12 NA 0 4 2013 1 1 4 40 28 62 250 13 NA 0 5 2013 1 1 5 39 28 64 260 13 NA 0 6 2013 1 1 6 38 28 67 240 12 NA 0 7 2013 1 1 7 39 28 64 240 15 NA 0 8 2013 1 1 8 40 28 62 250 10 NA 0 9 2013 1 1 9 40 28 62 260 15 NA 0 10 2013 1 1 10 41 28 60 260 14 NA 0 # … with 26,105 more rows, 1 more variable: pressure , and abbreviated # variable name ¹​wind_gust ``` ::: ::: ## The `mutate()` function - Another option is to use a combination of `across()` and `where()` functions. - The following code says: [apply the `mean()` function to **all the numerical columns**]{.text-outline} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-41_f4c49b07f8f9e37c53c2fe7f4be60e94'} ```{.r .cell-code} mutate(weather, across(where(is.numeric), round), .keep = "used") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 26,115 × 13 year month day hour temp dewp humid wind_dir wind_speed wind_g…¹ precip 1 2013 1 1 1 39 26 59 270 10 NA 0 2 2013 1 1 2 39 27 62 250 8 NA 0 3 2013 1 1 3 39 28 64 240 12 NA 0 4 2013 1 1 4 40 28 62 250 13 NA 0 5 2013 1 1 5 39 28 64 260 13 NA 0 6 2013 1 1 6 38 28 67 240 12 NA 0 7 2013 1 1 7 39 28 64 240 15 NA 0 8 2013 1 1 8 40 28 62 250 10 NA 0 9 2013 1 1 9 40 28 62 260 15 NA 0 10 2013 1 1 10 41 28 60 260 14 NA 0 # … with 26,105 more rows, 2 more variables: pressure , visib , and # abbreviated variable name ¹​wind_gust ``` ::: ::: ## The `summarise()` function - The `summarise()` function allows summarising columns from a data frame. - Compress a data frame into single values (i.e. one row). - Hence, you have to provide a function that will be used to calculate a certain value. ## The `summarise()` function Example 1: Calculate the mean/average values for the `dep_delay` and `arr_delay` columns. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-42_775a6bd7da0b9c24e97506353564ad60'} ```{.r .cell-code} summarise( flights, average_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay), average_arrival_delay = mean(arr_delay) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 2 average_departure_delay average_arrival_delay 1 NA NA ``` ::: ::: . . . What is going on? Why do we have NA's? ## The `summarise()` function Example 1: Calculate the mean/average values for the `dep_delay` and `arr_delay` columns. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-43_45da93a374ed17a363ecd6f25dfd4c30'} ```{.r .cell-code} summarise( flights, average_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), average_arrival_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 2 average_departure_delay average_arrival_delay 1 12.639 6.8954 ``` ::: ::: ## The `summarise()` function - It could be interesting to know how many observations were used in the computation. - For this, we can use the `n()` helper function. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-44_27235946fa6d01abfdcad624ed2c4af4'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-6|5"} summarise( flights, average_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), average_arrival_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n = n() # Adding a new column "n" with the number of used observations ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 3 average_departure_delay average_arrival_delay n 1 12.639 6.8954 336776 ``` ::: ::: ## The `summarise()` function - Similarly as with `mutate()`, we can use the `across()` function to avoid extra typing. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-45_d106ea0dc6ccdd1fb4bc8baa154fc491'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-5|3"} summarise( weather, across(where(is.numeric), mean, na.rm = TRUE), n = n() ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 14 year month day hour temp dewp humid wind_dir wind_speed wind_gust 1 2013 6.5037 15.675 11.491 55.260 41.440 62.530 199.76 10.517 25.487 # … with 4 more variables: precip , pressure , visib , n ``` ::: ::: ## Working with grouped data - Alone, the `summarise()` function is not helpful because it collapses a data frame to a single row. - Usually, we want to work on **grouped data**. - `group_by()` "prepares" a data frame to send it to the `summarise()` function. ## Working with grouped data Example 1: Calculate the average departure delay **by carrier**. First, let's group the data by `carrier`. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-46_1d3cd90d3d1d105f77c4a1cadb5f8410'} ```{.r .cell-code} flights_grouped <- group_by(flights, carrier) flights_grouped ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 336,776 × 19 # Groups: carrier [16] year month day dep_time sched_de…¹ dep_d…² arr_t…³ sched…⁴ arr_d…⁵ carrier 1 2013 1 1 517 515 2 830 819 11 UA 2 2013 1 1 533 529 4 850 830 20 UA 3 2013 1 1 542 540 2 923 850 33 AA 4 2013 1 1 544 545 -1 1004 1022 -18 B6 5 2013 1 1 554 600 -6 812 837 -25 DL 6 2013 1 1 554 558 -4 740 728 12 UA 7 2013 1 1 555 600 -5 913 854 19 B6 8 2013 1 1 557 600 -3 709 723 -14 EV 9 2013 1 1 557 600 -3 838 846 -8 B6 10 2013 1 1 558 600 -2 753 745 8 AA # … with 336,766 more rows, 9 more variables: flight , tailnum , # origin , dest , air_time , distance , hour , # minute , time_hour , and abbreviated variable names # ¹​sched_dep_time, ²​dep_delay, ³​arr_time, ⁴​sched_arr_time, ⁵​arr_delay ``` ::: ::: ## Working with grouped data Example 1: Calculate the average departure delay **by carrier**. Secondly, use `summarise()` as we did before by now using `flights_grouped` instead of `flights`. ::: {.cell output-location='slide' hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-47_06c7b7aab070e1eb48085a94b985ec03'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-5|2-3"} summarise( flights_grouped, average_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n = n() ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 16 × 3 carrier average_departure_delay n 1 9E 16.726 18460 2 AA 8.5860 32729 3 AS 5.8048 714 4 B6 13.023 54635 5 DL 9.2645 48110 6 EV 19.955 54173 7 F9 20.216 685 8 FL 18.726 3260 9 HA 4.9006 342 10 MQ 10.552 26397 11 OO 12.586 32 12 UA 12.106 58665 13 US 3.7824 20536 14 VX 12.869 5162 15 WN 17.712 12275 16 YV 18.996 601 ``` ::: ::: ## Working with grouped data - We can also `summarise()` multiple columns at once. ::: {.cell output-location='slide' hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-48_523483320f5478e7aa0ae32fa54d7ab2'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-5|3"} summarise( flights_grouped, across(where(is.numeric), mean, na.rm = TRUE), n = n() ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 16 × 16 carrier year month day dep_time sched…¹ dep_d…² arr_t…³ sched…⁴ arr_de…⁵ 1 9E 2013 6.5647 15.626 1486.5 1471.9 16.726 1639.0 1671.2 7.3797 2 AA 2013 6.4817 15.694 1297.3 1289.9 8.5860 1521.4 1545.1 0.36429 3 AS 2013 6.4146 15.793 1294.6 1284.5 5.8048 1564.9 1595.3 -9.9309 4 B6 2013 6.5239 15.764 1380.8 1397.2 13.023 1405.7 1469.4 9.4580 5 DL 2013 6.5748 15.772 1351.1 1346.4 9.2645 1572.9 1595.9 1.6443 6 EV 2013 6.5813 15.683 1368.6 1353.5 19.955 1488.1 1531.6 15.796 7 F9 2013 6.5942 15.616 1437.8 1407.8 20.216 1672.5 1645.6 21.921 8 FL 2013 6.0206 15.681 1386.5 1371.7 18.726 1574.0 1585.0 20.116 9 HA 2013 6.2749 15.737 948.76 974.39 4.9006 1474.2 1491.5 -6.9152 10 MQ 2013 6.4707 15.689 1392.6 1386.8 10.552 1550.8 1564.2 10.775 11 OO 2013 8.75 16.344 1725.2 1731.3 12.586 1913.2 1889.9 11.931 12 UA 2013 6.5618 15.704 1327.1 1312.7 12.106 1508.7 1544.2 3.5580 13 US 2013 6.5516 15.656 1231.3 1246.1 3.7824 1401.6 1411.7 2.1296 14 VX 2013 6.9345 15.737 1280.5 1264.7 12.869 1523.3 1596.3 1.7645 15 WN 2013 6.6305 15.692 1281.0 1260.2 17.712 1443.4 1450.4 9.6491 16 YV 2013 6.9068 15.755 1601.0 1574.5 18.996 1761.3 1743.4 15.557 # … with 6 more variables: flight , air_time , distance , # hour , minute , n , and abbreviated variable names # ¹​sched_dep_time, ²​dep_delay, ³​arr_time, ⁴​sched_arr_time, ⁵​arr_delay ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-49_21286a31f64fdbf5bf977594945223a3'} ::: ## Working with grouped data ::: {.callout-caution collapse="true" appearance="simple"} ## New in `dplyr` 1.1.0 `.by/by` is an experimental alternative to `group_by()` that supports per-operation grouping for `mutate()`, `summarise()`, `filter()`, and the `slice()` family. ::: [We want to calculate the average `height` for each combination of `species` and `homeworld` in the `starwars` data frame.]{.small} :::: {.columns .small} ::: {.column width='55%'} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-50_7fb9851d06c458ae1b823fb222888a87'} ```{.r .cell-code} starwars_grouped <- group_by(starwars, species, homeworld) summarise( starwars_grouped, mean_height = mean(height) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 58 × 3 # Groups: species [38] species homeworld mean_height 1 Aleena Aleen Minor 79 2 Besalisk Ojom 198 3 Cerean Cerea 198 4 Chagrian Champala 196 5 Clawdite Zolan 168 6 Droid Naboo 96 7 Droid Tatooine 132 8 Droid NA 9 Dug Malastare 112 10 Ewok Endor 88 # … with 48 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width='45%'} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-51_ed7114f4f94011d9003317bff0b35547'} ```{.r .cell-code} summarise( starwars, mean_height = mean(height), .by = c(species, homeworld) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 58 × 3 species homeworld mean_height 1 Human Tatooine 179.25 2 Droid Tatooine 132 3 Droid Naboo 96 4 Human Alderaan 176.33 5 Human Stewjon 182 6 Human Eriadu 180 7 Wookiee Kashyyyk 231 8 Human Corellia 175 9 Rodian Rodia 173 10 Hutt Nal Hutta 175 # … with 48 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: # Exercises {background-color="#2C404A"} ## The Titanic Using your newly acquired skills, try answering the following questions: 1. What was the average age of passengers on the Titanic? 2. How many passengers on the Titanic were from first class? 3. What was the proportion of passengers who survived the Titanic disaster? 4. What was the average ticket price by cabin class? ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-53_46512318249fffb27cdc5d32cbe44bcb'} ::: # Piping operations {background-color="#2C404A"} ![Photo by Val Tievsky on Unsplash](images/unsplash_pipe.jpg){fig-align="center"} ## Piping operations We have seen that to summarise grouped data, we need to perform two operations: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-54_55cc8d0c2f1aca949678e738e66b4dbd'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="1-7|1|3-7"} flights_grouped <- group_by(flights, carrier) res <- summarise( flights_grouped, average_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n = n() ) ``` ::: The thing is that we never directly use `flights_grouped`; it is only used as an **intermediate** object. ## Piping operations - With R 4.1.0+, we can use the pipe operator ([**|>**]{style="font-family:ubuntu;"}) to chain operations. - Basically, ([**|>**]{style="font-family:ubuntu;"}) takes the left-hand side (**lhs**) object and passes it as the first argument in the right-hand side (**rhs**) function. :::: {.columns .fragment} ::: {.column width="28%"} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-55_56e2b14498f94858d1d64dd95a36963b'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Same as log(10) 10 |> log() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 2.302585 ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="38%"} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-56_50a90adc0140883dab949d1f1d6db988'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Same has: # toupper("my string") "my string" |> toupper() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] "MY STRING" ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="34%"} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-57_0295deb87a43fd9f2a5a8d24e50d6fe3'} ```{.r .cell-code} # Same has: # head(chickwts), 6) chickwts |> head(6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` weight feed 1 179 horsebean 2 160 horsebean 3 136 horsebean 4 227 horsebean 5 217 horsebean 6 168 horsebean ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: ## Piping operations - Why is this useful? Because we can chain intermediate steps in data analysis. - For example: 1. Take `flights` and pass it as the first argument in `group_by()`. 2. Group the data based on the `carrier` column. 3. Summarise the data to calculate the average departure delay. ::: {.cell output-location='slide' hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-58_e1a3ed6423b15df4553a0d6a5601883d'} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|1|2|3-6|1-7"} flights |> # Take the flight data frame group_by(carrier) |> # Then group it by carrier summarise( # Then calculate the average departure delay (by group) average_departure_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n = n() ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 16 × 3 carrier average_departure_delay n 1 9E 16.726 18460 2 AA 8.5860 32729 3 AS 5.8048 714 4 B6 13.023 54635 5 DL 9.2645 48110 6 EV 19.955 54173 7 F9 20.216 685 8 FL 18.726 3260 9 HA 4.9006 342 10 MQ 10.552 26397 11 OO 12.586 32 12 UA 12.106 58665 13 US 3.7824 20536 14 VX 12.869 5162 15 WN 17.712 12275 16 YV 18.996 601 ``` ::: ::: ## Piping operations - By default, the pipe operator passes the **lhs** object as the first parameter in the **rhs** function. We can control this behaviour using the "**\_**" placeholder. - For example, `rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 1)` has three arguments. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-59_0bdd1c4fc84ff84565b7348ddd1ee791'} ```{.r .cell-code} 10 |> rnorm() # Same as rnorm(n = 10, mean = 0, sd = 1) 10 |> rnorm(5, mean = _) # Same as rnorm(5, mean = 10, sd = 1) ``` ::: . . . ::: {.callout-caution} ## Attention!!! You have to use the placeholder with named parameters. ::: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-60_fbd340df0bf5cbe4e35a0b4af9055df2'} ```{.r .cell-code} 10 |> rnorm(5, _) # Not good! 10 |> rnorm(5, mean = _) # Good! ``` ::: # Joining tables {background-color="#2C404A"} ## Joining tables - Data are rarely stored in a single data frame or a single file. - Good database practices recommend having similar data in separate tables. - Joins are used to **merge data frame** together. ## Understanding joins ## Understanding joins Suppose that we have two data frames: `sites` and `measurements`. . . . ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-61_cd1e9d370b82312a9f9feda24d6e052b'} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
The sites table contains information where about sampling locations
site_id latitude longitude
Site A 45.5231 -122.6765
Site B 46.1234 -123.4567
Site C 47.3456 -124.5678
``` ::: ::: . . . ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-62_d93b91dfcb3f3fe55d6a52a671e30573'} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
The measurements table contains temperature measurements
site_name temperature date
Site A 20.5 2020-01-01
Site A 21.3 2020-01-02
Site B 18.9 2020-02-01
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/export-join-tables_1e75894fd29d88e99885c3460b8cf9ea'} ::: ## Understanding joins If you want to follow along, you can read the toy data as this: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-64_bbb797ea3360b3f5d354e6e494715610'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites <- read_csv("https://bit.ly/3xAwqr1") measurements <- read_csv("https://bit.ly/3Sepl9a") ``` ::: ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-65_df3b3d23fbc88272116b416e5fcd76c4'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 2 Site B 46.123 -123.46 3 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} measurements ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_name temperature date 1 Site A 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ## Left joins ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-66_a11ceaa5f4501b68c608390008610df0'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 2 Site B 46.123 -123.46 3 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} measurements ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_name temperature date 1 Site A 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ::: If we try to join `sites` and `measurements` together, we get the following error. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-67_a14685206efb83ef8d6aeb1e0d573cad'} ```{.r .cell-code} left_join(sites, measurements) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-error} ``` Error in `left_join()`: ! `by` must be supplied when `x` and `y` have no common variables. ℹ Use `cross_join()` to perform a cross-join. ``` ::: ::: . . . :::{.callout-tip collapse=false appearance='default' icon=true} ## Good practice The `*_join()` family functions will try to automatically join tables using columns with the same names. However, it is of good practice to be explicit on which columns to use with the `by` argument. ::: ## Left joins - We can specify the columns to use for the join with the `by` argument. - The following code says: [Use the `site_id` column in `sites`]{.text-outline} [and the `site_name` column in `measurements`]{.text-outline} to join both tables together. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-68_c70bd2d85f6a07e81564f6ae79b87597'} ```{.r .cell-code} left_join(sites, measurements, by = c("site_id" = "site_name")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 4 × 5 site_id latitude longitude temperature date 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 45.523 -122.68 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 46.123 -123.46 18.9 2020-02-01 4 Site C 47.346 -124.57 NA NA ``` ::: ::: ## Inner joins ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-69_cc285147a454e00ca426cb62d03bcb48'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 2 Site B 46.123 -123.46 3 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} measurements ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_name temperature date 1 Site A 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ::: An `inner_join()` [keeps only the observations that match between the tables.]{.text-outline} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-70_e6675eabbb7f2203d20b5db378c1c099'} ```{.r .cell-code} inner_join(sites, measurements, by = c("site_id" = "site_name")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 5 site_id latitude longitude temperature date 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 45.523 -122.68 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 46.123 -123.46 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ## Full joins ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-71_97d715202f2e2462629c7e4916779e96'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 2 Site B 46.123 -123.46 3 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} measurements ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_name temperature date 1 Site A 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ::: A `full_join()` [keeps all the observations contained in the tables.]{.text-outline} `NA` will be used as a fill value when there are no matches. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-72_9bcd8182459d2adcd18b066e7dec91e6'} ```{.r .cell-code} full_join(sites, measurements, by = c("site_id" = "site_name")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 4 × 5 site_id latitude longitude temperature date 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 45.523 -122.68 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 46.123 -123.46 18.9 2020-02-01 4 Site C 47.346 -124.57 NA NA ``` ::: ::: ## Anti joins ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-73_e75221c72874da730993c978d6f6d203'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 2 Site B 46.123 -123.46 3 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} measurements ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_name temperature date 1 Site A 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ::: An `anti-join()` find all observations that have no match between tables. The next bloc of code says: [find all observations in `sites` that have no match in `measurements`]{.text-outline} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-74_69bf947305d22cd5990cf0b519a35ab6'} ```{.r .cell-code} anti_join(sites, measurements, by = c("site_id" = "site_name")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ::: ## Anti joins ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-75_58eac05ad5d59d6bf4656935ad2b85b0'} ```{.r .cell-code} sites ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_id latitude longitude 1 Site A 45.523 -122.68 2 Site B 46.123 -123.46 3 Site C 47.346 -124.57 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} measurements ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 3 site_name temperature date 1 Site A 20.5 2020-01-01 2 Site A 21.3 2020-01-02 3 Site B 18.9 2020-02-01 ``` ::: ::: ::: If we inverse the order of the data frames, we get a different result. The next bloc of code says: [find all observations in `measurements` that have no match in `sites`]{.text-outline} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-76_826495bbb412e334e964904f051a773e'} ```{.r .cell-code} anti_join(measurements, sites, by = c("site_name" = "site_id")) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 0 × 3 # … with 3 variables: site_name , temperature , date ``` ::: ::: ## Inequality and rolling joins So far, we have joined tables on the exact match: **both tables need to have columns sharing the same value**. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-77_9663b484c7c871768f11678b8cee890f'} ::: Now, consider these two data frames to merge using the `depth_m` column. :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='50%'} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-78_89d3ba76e36f748ef415d10ca2fc4c3c'} ```{.r .cell-code} df_temperature ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 2 depth_m chla 1 1.1 0.1 2 1.4 0.3 ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width='50%'} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-79_37a1bc4bf9031aca68bad8d4197cbfce'} ```{.r .cell-code} df_o2 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 2 depth_m doxy 1 1.12 200 2 1.2 250 ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: . . . What will happen if I try to join them? ## Inequality joins Joining these table **is not working** because there are no values of `depth_m` that match between `df_temperature` and `df_o2` ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-80_8b4a8d7f4a8cb2a4a794bd473ffe7540'} ```{.r .cell-code} df_temperature ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 2 depth_m chla 1 1.1 0.1 2 1.4 0.3 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} df_o2 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 2 depth_m doxy 1 1.12 200 2 1.2 250 ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: {.columns .small} ::: {.column width='50%'} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-81_cd8ee3c869178de07d1381c6441f7ec6'} ```{.r .cell-code} left_join(df_temperature, df_o2, by = "depth_m") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 3 depth_m chla doxy 1 1.1 0.1 NA 2 1.4 0.3 NA ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width='50%'} ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-82_68d977018b9dfe8c979ed4d562ba36b2'} ```{.r .cell-code} inner_join(df_temperature, df_o2, by = "depth_m") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 0 × 3 # … with 3 variables: depth_m , chla , doxy ``` ::: ::: ::: :::: ## Inequality joins Because there are no exact matches in the `depth_m` column, we can use an inequality join with the `join_by()` function. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-83_ad98b9b0b749da088c70e9a92c2a3240'} ```{.r .cell-code} left_join(df_temperature, df_o2, by = join_by(depth_m <= depth_m)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 4 depth_m.x chla depth_m.y doxy 1 1.1 0.1 1.12 200 2 1.1 0.1 1.2 250 3 1.4 0.3 NA NA ``` ::: ::: The previous bloc of code says: [left join `df_temperature` and `df_o2`]{.fragment .text-outline} [where `depth_m` in `df_temperature` is smaller or equal to `depth_m` in `df_o2`]{.fragment .text-outline} ## Inequality joins ::: {.small} ::: {.cell layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-84_a4a4162210887bfcae6168227fe1e409'} ```{.r .cell-code} df_temperature ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 2 depth_m chla 1 1.1 0.1 2 1.4 0.3 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} df_o2 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 2 depth_m doxy 1 1.12 200 2 1.2 250 ``` ::: ::: ::: Note that there are two rows in `df_o2` that match the specified condition. This is why we end up with three rows after joining. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-85_0d71e335a1ce1382d3ee9c5f815893a6'} ```{.r .cell-code} left_join(df_temperature, df_o2, by = join_by(depth_m <= depth_m)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 3 × 4 depth_m.x chla depth_m.y doxy 1 1.1 0.1 1.12 200 2 1.1 0.1 1.2 250 3 1.4 0.3 NA NA ``` ::: ::: ## Rolling joins Instead of using an inequality join, we can try a rolling join. This type of join limits the results returned from an inequality join condition and uses the `closest()` function. ::: {.cell hash='index_cache/revealjs/unnamed-chunk-86_da8c30e8541773397c2f1e0fa411a0b1'} ```{.r .cell-code} left_join(df_temperature, df_o2, by = join_by(closest(depth_m <= depth_m))) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2 × 4 depth_m.x chla depth_m.y doxy 1 1.1 0.1 1.12 200 2 1.4 0.3 NA NA ``` ::: ::: The previous bloc of code says: [left join `df_temperature` and `df_o2`]{.fragment .text-outline} [where `depth_m` in `df_temperature` is smaller or equal to `depth_m` in `df_o2`]{.fragment .text-outline} [**but** only keep the closest match]{.fragment .text-outline} ## Exercise Your turn: Find the # Time to practice {background-color="#2C404A"} 1 - Work on your data 2 - SQL Murder Mystery: [https://mystery.knightlab.com/](https://mystery.knightlab.com/) # SQL Murder Mystery {background-color="#2C404A"} ![Photo by Matt Popovich on Unsplash](images/unsplash_police_car.jpg){fig-align="center"} ## SQL Murder Mystery :::: {.columns} ::: {.column width='40%'} > There's been a Murder in SQL City! <script>
  // htmlwidgets need to know to resize themselves when slides are shown/hidden.
  // Fire the "slideenter" event (handled by htmlwidgets.js) when the current
  // slide changes (different for each slide format).
  (function () {
    // dispatch for htmlwidgets
    function fireSlideEnter() {
      const event = window.document.createEvent("Event");
      event.initEvent("slideenter", true, true);
      window.document.dispatchEvent(event);
    }

    function fireSlideChanged(previousSlide, currentSlide) {
      fireSlideEnter();

      // dispatch for shiny
      if (window.jQuery) {
        if (previousSlide) {
          window.jQuery(previousSlide).trigger("hidden");
        }
        if (currentSlide) {
          window.jQuery(currentSlide).trigger("shown");
        }
      }
    }

    // hookup for slidy
    if (window.w3c_slidy) {
      window.w3c_slidy.add_observer(function (slide_num) {
        // slide_num starts at position 1
        fireSlideChanged(null, w3c_slidy.slides[slide_num - 1]);
      });
    }

  })();
</script>
